22 SECTION 12. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1250.4a of Title 36, unless
24 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
Req. No. 17179 Page 30

1 A. The Insurance Commissioner's dispute resolution program
2 shall help consumers and insurance companies effectively,
3 economically, fairly, and timely resolve disputes with persons or
4 entities subject to the jurisdiction of the Insurance Commissioner
5 and related to insurance or service warranty claims. The dispute
6 resolution program shall be subject to the laws and protections of
7 the Dispute Resolution Act, Sections 1801 through 1813 of Title 12
8 of the Oklahoma Statutes, and the rules promulgated thereto.
9 B. Mediation may be requested only by the policyholder, as a
10 first-party claimant or the insurer.
11 C. Mediation is voluntary except that insurers shall
12 participate in any mediation requested by a first-party claimant
13 that meets the following criteria:
14 1. Involves an insurance claim under a personal residential
15 insurance policy or personal automobile insurance policy; and
16 2. No civil litigation has commenced relating to the claim to
17 be mediated.
18 D. For purposes of this section, the term "claim" refers to any
19 dispute between an insurer and a policyholder relating to a material
20 issue of fact other than a dispute:
21 1. With respect to which the insurer has a reasonable basis to
22 suspect fraud;
23
24
Req. No. 17179 Page 31

1 2. When, based on all the information presented to the
2 Insurance Commissioner as to the cause of loss, there appears to be
3 no coverage under the policy;
4 3. With respect to which the insurer has a reasonable basis to
5 believe that the policyholder has intentionally made a material
6 misrepresentation of fact which is relevant to the claim, and the
7 entire request for payment of a loss has been denied on the basis of
8 the material misrepresentation;
9 4. When, based on all of the information presented to the
10 Insurance Commissioner, the policyholder appears to have suffered no
11 actual monetary or property loss;
12 5. When a claim is outside the time frames prescribed in
13 applicable law; or
14 6. When a claim has been paid in full prior to any mediation
15 conference held pursuant to this section.
16 E. A claim shall not be eligible for mediation unless it has
17 first been submitted and fully processed through the Oklahoma
18 Insurance Department's consumer complaint program.
19 F. All parties to the mediation must negotiate in good faith to
20 resolve the dispute and must have the authority to immediately
21 settle the claim; however, there is no requirement that the dispute
22 be resolved in mediation. If a written settlement is reached and
23 the policyholder is not represented by an attorney, the policyholder
24 has three (3) business days within which the policyholder may
Req. No. 17179 Page 32

1 resc ind the settlement unless the policyholder has cashed or
2 deposited any check, draft, or other payment made to the
3 policyholder as a result of the settlement. If a settlement
4 agreement is reached and is not rescinded, it shall be binding and
5 act as a release of all specific claims presented in the mediation
6 conference.
7 G. The mediation conference shall be held as scheduled by the
8 dispute resolution program coordinator. Upon application by any
9 party for a continuance, the program coordinator shall, for good
10 cause shown or if neither party objects, grant a continuance and
11 shall notify all parties of the date and place of the rescheduled
12 conference. Good cause also includes severe illness, injury, or
13 other emergency that could not be controlled by the party and could
14 not reasonably be remedied by the party prior to the conference by
15 providing a replacement representative or otherwise. Good cause
16 includes the necessity of obtaining additional information, securing
17 the attendance of a necessary professional, or the avoidance of
18 significant financial hardship. If the policyholder demonstrates to
19 the mediator the need for an expedited mediation conference due to
20 an undue hardship, the conference shall be conducted at the earliest
21 date convenient to all of the parties and the mediator. Undue
22 hardship will be demonstrated when holding the conference on a non-
23 expedited basis would interfere with or contradict the treatment of
24 a severe illness or injury, substantially impair a party's ability
Req. No. 17179 Page 33

1 to a ssert their position at the conference, result in significant
2 financial hardship, or other reasonably justified grounds.
3 H. An insurer will be deemed to have failed to appear if the
4 insurer's representative lacks authority to settle the full value of
5 the claim. The authority to settle the claim includes the ability
6 to disburse the full settlement amount within ten (10) days of the
7 conclusion of the conference. The insurer shall produce at the
8 conference a copy of the policy.
9 I. Any violation by an insurer of this section shall subject
10 the insurer to discipline including a civil penalty of not more than
11 Ten Thousand Dollars ($10,000.00), in addition to any other
12 penalties provided for by law.
13 J. The Insurance Commissioner may adopt and promulgate rules
14 for the implementation and administration of this section,
15 including, but not limited to, the amount and who is responsible for
16 the payment of any fees in the event costs of the program are not
17 fully covered by the Administrative Office of the Courts, and the
18 expansion or restriction of eligibility criteria for claims subject
19 to mandatory and voluntary mediation under this section.
