Req. No. 17179 Page 35

1 SECTION 14. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1250.6a of Title 36, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. An insurer issuing a personal lines residential property
5 insurance policy in this state must provide a Homeowner Claims Bill
6 of Rights to policyholders on the insurer's company website. The
7 purpose of the bill of rights is to summarize, in simple,
8 nontechnical terms, existing Oklahoma law regarding the rights of a
9 personal lines residential property insurance policyholder who files
10 a claim of loss. The Homeowner Claims Bill of Rights is specific to
11 the claims process and does not represent all of a policyholder's
12 rights under Oklahoma law regarding the insurance policy. The
13 Homeowner Claims Bill of Rights does not enlarge, modify, or
14 contravene statutory requirements, including, but not limited to,
15 Sections 1204, 1250.6, 1250.7, and 6202 of Title 36 of the Oklahoma
16 Statutes and OAC 365:1-11, and does not prohibit an insurer from
17 exercising any right to repair damaged property in compliance with
18 the terms of an applicable policy. The Homeowner Claims Bill of
19 Rights must, at a minimum, state:
20 HOMEOWNER CLAIMS BILL OF RIGHTS
21 This Bill of Rights is specific to the claims process and
22 does not represent all of your rights under Oklahoma law
23 regarding your policy. This document does not prohibit an
24 insurer from exercising any right to repair damaged
Req. No. 17179 Page 36

1 property in compliance with the terms of an applicable
2 policy.
3 YOU HAVE THE RIGHT TO:
4 1. Receive from your insurance company an acknowledgment of
5 your reported claim within fourteen (14) days after the time you
6 communicated the claim.
7 2. Receive from your insurance company within thirty (30) days
8 after you have submitted an executed proof of loss statement to your
9 insurance company, confirmation that your claim is accepted or
10 denied or if further investigation is necessary.
11 3. Receive from your insurance company a copy of any detailed
12 estimate of the amount of the loss within seven (7) days after the
13 estimate is generated by the insurance company's adjuster.
14 4. Receive from your insurance company within sixty (60) days
15 after you have submitted an executed proof of loss statement either:
16 a. full settlement payment for your claim or payment of
17 the undisputed portion of your claim,
18 b. denial of your claim, or
19 c. notice that the insurer needs more time to investigate
20 the claim and stating the reasons why.
21 5. If insurer provides notice that it needs more time to
22 investigate the claim, receive from your insurance company within
23 ninety (90) days after you have submitted an executed proof of loss
24 statement either:
Req. No. 17179 Page 37

1 a. full settlement payment for your claim or payment of
2 the undisputed portion of your claim, or
3 b. denial of your claim.
4 In the event of a weather-related catastrophe or a major
5 natural disaster, as declared by the Governor, the
6 Insurance Commissioner may approve a request to extend
7 this deadline an additional twenty (20) days.
8 6. Contact the Oklahoma Insurance Department via telephone or
9 website for assistance with any insurance claim or questions
10 pertaining to the handling of your claim.
11 YOU ARE ADVISED TO:
12 1. File all claims directly with your insurance company.
13 2. Contact your insurance company before entering into any
14 contract for repairs to confirm any managed repair policy provisions
15 or optional preferred vendors.
16 3. Make and document emergency repairs that are necessary to
17 prevent further damage. Keep the damaged property, if feasible,
18 keep all receipts, and take photographs or video of damage before
19 and after any repairs to provide to your insurer.
20 4. Carefully read any contract that requires you to pay out-of-
21 pocket expenses or a fee that is based on a percentage of the
22 insurance proceeds that you will receive for repairing or replacing
23 your property.
24
Req. No. 17179 Page 38

1 5. Confirm that the contractor you choose is licensed to do
2 business in Oklahoma. You can verify a contractor's license and
3 check to see if there are any complaints against him or her by using
4 the Oklahoma Construction Industries Board's website. You should
5 also ask the contractor for references from previous work.
6 6. Require all contractors to provide proof of insurance before
7 beginning repairs.
8 7. Take precautions if the damage requires you to leave your
9 home, including securing your property and turning off your gas,
10 water, and electricity, and contacting your insurance company and
11 provide a phone number where you can be reached.
12 B. Any violation of this section shall be a violation of the
13 Unfair Claims Settlement Practices Act, and the Insurance
14 Commissioner may, after notice and opportunity for a hearing,
15 subject an insurer to the civil penalties set forth in Sections
16 1250.13 and 1250.14 of this title, along with any other penalties
17 set forth in applicable law.
